1. Introduction
Flux is the first temporal-causal programming language designed exclusively for the Ex Nihilo operating system. It knows no files, processes, or irreversible errors. Instead, it works with intentions, probabilities, and timelines that can be rewritten or abandoned.

This manual will teach you how to:

write programs that don’t “run,” but become reality in consensual time;

manipulate streams of intentions without fear of being completely wrong;

use the power of paradoxes as a mechanism for security and creativity.

Warning: Flux is not a classical language. If you try to write a C-like function or allocate memory with malloc, the system will create a benign paradox and ask you if you want to rewrite the past.

2. Fundamental concepts
2.1 Intent
The atomic unit of execution. An intent is a statement of the form:
“Under certain conditions, with a certain priority, let a sequence of actions happen.”

Intentions never stop – they either come true or become ghost branches.

2.2 Timeline
An alternate timeline. Every decision or mistake creates a new timeline. All timelines coexist in the causal mosaic.

2.3 Persistent probability
Any value or state can be expressed as a probability (0..1). For example, x = 0.8 means "x exists in 80% of the relevant timelines".

2.4 Collapse
When a probabilistic expression needs to become a concrete result – for example, to be displayed to the user – a collapse (maximum weight, average or random) is applied.

2.5 Causal hardening
A rare and expensive mechanism that makes a time interval irreversible. After hardening, not even the creator can rewrite that part of reality. The equivalent of a commit in classical systems.

3. Installation and tools
Flux is part of the Ex Nihilo distribution. On a standard system, the compiler is called fluxc.

bash
# Check version
fluxc --version
# Help
fluxc --help
Included tools:

fluxc – compiler (lexer + parser + semantic analyzer + bytecode generator)

tvm – Time Virtual Machine (runs bytecode)

fluxdbg – symbolic debugger (allows you to "travel" between timelines)

4. Basic syntax
Flux uses a syntax similar to a mix between Python and Rust, but with specific keywords.

4.1 Comments
flux
# This is a comment (until the end of the line)
4.2 Identifiers
Alphanumeric and underscore, cannot start with a digit. Context sensitive (not case sensitive).

4.3 Primitive Data Types
Type Example Remarks
probability 0.85 always between 0 and 1
int 42 classical integer
float 3.14 floating point
string "Hello, Ex Nihilo" character sequence
duration 10s, 250ms, 2cycles units: s, ms, ns, cycles
interval [1s, 5s] closed temporal interval
timeline tl_main reference to a temporal branch
4.4 Operators
Arithmetic: +, -, *, /

Comparison: ==, !=, <, >, <=, >=

Logical: and, or, not

Temporal: after, before, in_time

4.5 Control Structures
flow
if condition : {
# then
} else : {
# else
}

for i in [1, 10] : {
# loop with iteration over a collection
}

in_time_condition : {
# paradox-risk loop – use with caution
}
5. Declarations
5.1 Intent
flow
intent <name> {
trigger: <event>
priority: <0..1>
condition: <boolean_expression>
execute: {
<instructions>
}
}
trigger – the event that activates the intent (e.g. at_first_cognitive_sign(), every 10s, after event X)

priority – how likely this intent is to be chosen when several are pending

condition – additionally checked before execution

5.2 Flow
A flow is a sequence of causally related intents. Similar to a function, but runs in its own timeline.

flow
flow name(param1, param2) {
<instructions>
}
5.3 Structure
flow
structure Name {
field1: type,
field2: type,
...
}
5.4 Function
flow
function add(a: probability, b: probability) -> probability {
return a + b;
}
5.5 Causal mosaic
Declare a region of causal space (“directory” without files).

flow
causal_mosaic user_data = {
components: temporal_sparse_matrix(),
policies: { write: "add_branch", read: "most_likely" }
};
6. Instructions and expressions
6.1 Sending sensation (instead of printing)
flow
send_sensation("mental image", "content", 2s);
send_sensation("inner speech", "text");
send_sensation("tactile sensation", "vibration", 500ms);

6.2 Listening to user intent
flow
response = listen_intent(user, 10s, "default");
6.3 Probabilistic collapse
flow
concrete_value = collapse(probabilistic_expression, "maximum_weight");
# methods: "maximum_weight", "average", "random"
6.4 Creating a new timeline
flow
new_tl = create_timeline(from: current_timeline(), weight: 0.3);
6.5 Causal closure
flow
causal_closure(interval: [present - 1s, present + 1s], maximum_cost: 0.001);
6.6 Controlled paradox generation
flow
paradox = trigger_paradox(type: "simple_causal_cycle", interval: [now, now+5s]);
solve_paradox(paradox, method: "multiple_collapse_with_humor");
7. Managing time and probability
7.1 Time units
1s – one causal second (can be shorter or longer than physical time)

10ms – ten milliseconds

1cycle – one cycle of the time scheduler

7.2 Default probability
If you don't specify a probability, a value or action has probability 1.0 in the current timeline.

7.3 The with_probability operator
flow
x = 42 with_probability 0.9; # x is 42 in 90% of timelines
7.4 Native temporal functions
now() – current causal moment

intent_duration(intent) – how long an intent was active

delay(duration) – suspends the current timeline


8. Causal file system (mosaic)
There are no files, only components in a mosaic. Access is done by keys.

stream
# Write (creates a new branch)
causal_mosaic.access(key: "user.answer").write(value, weight=0.8);

# Read (automatically collapses)
result = causal_mosaic.access(key: "user.answer", paradox_tolerance: 0.2).read();
Mosaic policies can be:

write: "add_branch" (never overwrite)

write: "merge_timeline" (merge with existing timeline)

read: "most_probable", read: "all", read: "random"

9. Paradoxes and security
The Ex Nihilo system uses paradoxes as a method of authentication and protection.

9.1 The Security Paradox
On an unauthorized attempt, the system generates an event that is impossible to reproduce (e.g. a sequence of 3 random prime numbers). The user must "match" that pattern without knowing it - otherwise his timeline is reset.

9.2 Manually triggering a paradox
flow
security_paradox.manual_trigger(type: "random_prime_interval", length: 3);
9.3 Handling paradoxes
flow
if detect_paradox_local() then {
resolve_paradox(method: "multiple_collapse", involved: [current_user]);
}
10. Compiling and running
10.1 Compiling
bash
fluxc program.flux
This command generates a .fluxb (bytecode) file.

10.2 Running
bash
tvm program.fluxb [--timeline main] [--prob-threshold 0.5]
10.3 Interactive mode (REPL)
bash
fluxc repl
You can write intents directly and see them collapse in real time.

10.4 Compilation options
Option Effect
--dump-ast displays the abstract syntax tree
--dump-bytecode displays the generated instructions
--semantic-only only checks for correctness, does not generate bytecode
--optimize tries to reduce the number of parasitic timelines
11. Debugging and “welcome” mistakes
In Flux, there are no compilation errors in the classical sense. A syntactic or semantic mistake simply creates a very low-probability branch, which can be ignored or explored.

11.1 Debugging Tools
fluxdbg – attach to a timeline and travel forward/backward

Debugger Commands:

timeline list – show all active branches

switch <id> – change the current timeline

collapse prob – force collapse of a probability

rewrite [interval] – undo the last actions (if not committed)

11.2 Common Mistakes (and how to turn them into an advantage)
Mistake What Flux does How to use it creatively
Undefined variable Creates a timeline where the variable exists by default You can “teach” the system to define the variable from the context
Infinite loop Turns it into an educational paradox Generates unique temporal keys for security
Access to uninitialized memory Returns probability 0.5 (“may exist”) Use to test hypotheses
12. Complete Examples
12.1 Hello, Ex Nihilo
flux
intent Hello {
trigger: at_first_cognitive_sign()
execute: {
send_sensation("mental image", "✨ Welcome to the world without files! ✨", 3s);
}
}
12.2 Probability calculator
flow
function calculate_chance(event: string) -> probability {
if event == "rain tomorrow" : {
return 0.3;
} else : {
return 0.5;
}
}

intent TestProb {
trigger: every 1s
execute: {
chance = calculate_chance("rain tomorrow");
message = "The chance of rain is " ++ collapse(chance, "maximum_weight");
send_sensation("inner speech", message, 1s);
}
}
12.3 Writing and Reading in Mosaic
flow
causal_mosaic user_memory = {
components: temporal_sparse_matrix(),
policies: { write: "add_branch", read: "most_likely" }
};

intent Memory {
trigger: every_10_causal_seconds
execute: {
# write a thought
user_memory.access(key: "last_thought").write("I forgot something...", weight=0.9);

# read
memory = user_memory.access(key: "last_thought").read();
send_sensation("inner_talk", "I remember: " ++ memory, 1s);
}
}
